node.text:
Our @usaf_thunderbird_maintainers have completed their first-ever local conversion of an F-16 Fighting Falcon, Tail Number A91-0470.

This process saved time, money, and manpower as well as reduced the completion time by more than 100 days.

For years the maintenance team has had the capabilities to convert a traditional gray F-16 to a Thunderbirds F-16 and in October 2020, the team moved forward with that effort.

An enlisted maintenance team was developed and assigned to the project with one mission... to convert 470.

212 days later, on May 5, 2021, they succeeded.

node.title: Thunderbirds accelerate change with first-ever F-16 conversion

and a culture of inclusiveness and belonging across our Air Force.

I don't have the answers, but I do know there is no room for bigotry, hatred or small mindedness in our force. Period. Every member of our team needs to know we have their back.

So let's start the conversation acknowledging we have many valued Airmen who live and work for One Nation under God, indivisible ... but for them ... without liberty and justice for all.” -Gen. David Goldfein / Chief of Staff, U.S. Air Force

Melvin Williams is a pilot and general aviation enthusiast who has been around airplanes his entire life. 

He graduated from Aviation High School in Long Island City, Queens, and currently works in the airline industry teaching fellow aviation maintenance technicians. 

Williams, inspired by his passion for aviation, also teaches underprivileged students within the Atlanta area about aviation careers that he didn’t know about at their age.

We all go through Phases, especially our jets when they hit a certain number of flight hours!
When a jet goes through Phase, almost every panel is removed and inspected for cracks and general wear and tear. Once everything is inspected it’s then put back together and ready to hit the skies!

Ryan Nabel is a police officer with the Dayton Police Department in Dayton, Ohio. He’s also an Army Veteran and Medal of Valor recipient. 

He and five other officers responded to a mass shooting in Dayton’s Oregon District in 2019. Within 30 seconds of engaging, they stopped the shooter and prevented what could have been many more deaths.

All six officers were awarded the Public Safety Officer Medal of Valor, the highest decoration for bravery exhibited by public safety officers in the United States.

We salute Ryan and the additional five officers who put their lives at risk for their community.

We teamed up today with the @usarmyreserve out of New Century, Kansas, to catch a ride in one of their CH-47F Chinooks to get a glimpse of Kansas City and witness the capabilities of a twin-engined, heavy-lift helicopter!

Air power comes in all shapes and sizes — So, whether you’re pulling 9 Gs in a multi-role fighter jet or maintaining a stable hover to off-load cargo, there’s a team of Airmen, Sailors, Soldiers, and Marines ready to deliver that air power at a moments notice.
